Ex-Southmark Aide,
   Grosz, Pleads Innocent
   To U.S. Fraud Charges
Mr. Grosz previously served as senior vice president of
San Jacinto Savings and as president of Southmark Funding,
another unit of Dallas-based Southmark. His indictment on
Dec. 11 was the first to arise from an investigation of
Southmark and San Jacinto Savings by the U.S. Justice
Department's Dallas Bank Fraud Task Force.
   The 12 charges against Mr. Grosz carry a maximum penalty
of 60 years in prison and a $3 million fine.